x0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMalaysia has long been a melting pot of various cultures and ethnicities, including the three largest populations, the Malay, Chinese, and Indians. Despite this, efforts to implement multilingualism, advocated by language educators and policy makers, have been marred by political and religious affiliations. Drawing on two decades of field research, this timely analysis of language variation in Malaysia is an important contribution to the understanding not only of linguistic pluralism in the country, but also of the Indian Diaspora, and of the effects of language change on urban migrant populations. The research presented here will be of interest to scholars of Southeast Asian and South Asian Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlagappar, Ponmalar N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Maya Khemlani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Maya Khemlani, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDealwis, Caesar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumanig, Francisco Perlas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJan, Jariah Mohd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, Mahmud Hasan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKärchner-Ober, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMukherjee, Dipika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMukherjee, Dipika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNambiar, Mohana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c